Sex workers marched in Kenya's capital to call for the legalization of their trade.
Al-Shebab militants threw grenades from a moving car at a bus station, killing at least five and injuring dozens more.
notes: Al-Shebab initially denied responsibility for the attack.

issuenote: Armed men pulled two suspected Al-Shebab sympathizers off of a bus and kidnapped them. One was later found dead.
notes: Many believed the kidnappers to be police frustrated with the legal limits on action.

issuenote: Armed men pulled two suspected Al-Shebab sympathizers off of a bus and kidnapped them. One was later found dead.

Members of a separatist political faction protested outside a court house to challenge a legal ban on their organization. One protestor was killed by a thrown rock.

A police convoy hit an improvised IED, killing one and injuring several others.
Gunmen opened fire on and tossed grenades into a popular restraunt, killing one. One attacker was arrested.

Attackers tossed grenades into a restruant and shop near the border region, injuring four.
Attackers detonated a bomb as aid workers distributed non-food items to refugees. Several were injured.

After the Pokomo farming community protested the pastoralist Orma grazing cattle on their farms, the Orma responded with violence. The next week Pokomo villagers raided an Orma village, killing dozens.
Muslims rioted and called for violence after the radical cleric Aboud Rogo Mohammed was shot and killed. Cars and churches were targeted in the ensuing violence.
notes: Mohammed's widow and human rights groups blamed the police for his death, calling it an extra-judicial killing. The police claimed no part in his death and even blamed it on Al-Shebab.

A candidate for one of Kisumu's parliamentary seats was shot and killed while in his car. Locals rioted in response, accusing the police of being lax or even supporting the murder. Three rioters were killed in a building, but it was uncertain if this was due to tear gas or an electrical fire.

The weeks of strikes in the Bophuthatswana homeland culminate in violence.  Hundreds of Afrikaner white militiamen pour into the homeland to prop up the rule of the black president.  Gunfights follow between the whites and the regional police.
notes: Contains both pro and anti-government violence, with elements of a coup.

issuenote: Black gunmen enter a Ba'hai church and kill 3 Iranian worshippers.
Inkatha Freedom Party supporters occupy a stadium where the ANC is due to give a rally.  Clashes erupt.  5 die.

About 3000 prison inmates begin work stoppages and marches across South Africa to protest against exclusion from upcoming election.  In some prisons, the warders use tear gas, rubber bullets, and dogs.
notes: End date occurs when Transitional Council grants prisoners the right to vote.

issuenote: 200 National Party supporters throw stones and bottles at ANC supporters during a rally by Nelson Mandela.
Ongoing violence between ANC and IFP.
A tense stand-off/protest ensues between ANC and Inkatha Freedom Party supporters ahead of an ANC rally.  The situation nearly turns into a riot, but police keep them apart with tear gas.

Police and civil servants strike in the Ciskei region because they fear losing their pay and benefits once Apartheid ends and the region is dissolved.  They take fellow officers and wives hostage.  The strike leads to rioting and looting.
Tens of thousands of ANC supporters march to demand free electioneering and to show ANC support in the traditional Zulu stronghold.
Factional clashes leave 70 dead over a several day period.
notes: Following this, South Africa takes direct control of Natal province.

issuenote: Thousands of Zulus organized by the IFP march to protest the upcoming election.  ANC guards fire on them, killing many.  ANC and Zulus battle across the city.  Fighting continues for several days.
notes: This is the first time the black township violence has spread to central Johannesburg.

issuenote: Gunmen kill 5 ANC supporters.
notes: Deaths in March are 552, more than half in Natal.

issuenote: Ongoing black violence in Natal, including an incident at a church in Estcourt, where gunmen kill 5 worshippers.

issuenote: 21 die in politically related violence.

issuenote: Unidentified gunmen attack election workers distributing pamphlets.
IFP and ANC supporters clash over three week period, leaving 7 dead at the Western Areas gold mine.

A bombing spree perpetrated by whites.  On 4/24, a car bomb kills 9 people in Johannesburg near the ANC headquarters.  On 4/25, a bomb destroys a taxi stand used by black commuters in Pretoria.  Another bomb explodes the same day in Gerimston.

The mutiny was staged out of the Ivatu military base near Antananarivo after renegade soldiers killed the officer sent to negotiatie with them.  Soldiers who participated in the mutiny were reportedly paid to do so.

Following an attempted mutiny, soldiers cut power to opposition radio Free FM, keeping it off the air for over 7 hours.  The military then gathered outside the station, causing its staff to take their equiptment and flee.  Soldiers late seized a computer screen and a voltage regulator.

Clashes occur in the town of Douz.  The cause is unknown.

Fighting between rival clans over access to jobs.

Dozens of protesters demand that militia fighters pull out of the capital.

People in Khadafi's home town protest against the town's marginalization in the 'New Libya.'

actor1: Students of University of Ghar Yunis
issuenote: As many as four thousand students of the University of Ghar Yunis and former rebels gathered in Benghazi to protest the transitional government's lack of transparency. Protests led to the resignation of the National Transitional Council deputy. The NTC headquarters were also attacked by protesters.

Mistrata militiamen attacked members of the Al-Zawiyah militia in Tripoli, resulting in the death of four militants and the wounding of some five others. The Mistrata militants were allegedly attempting to rescue a comrade detained by the Al-Zawiyah militia.

Responding to the stabbing of a fellow townsmen, The Martyrs Brigade of Gharyan  entered Asbi'a and were  confronted by the Asbi'a's militia . The ensuing conflict lasted three days and claimed the lives of four. An estimated fifty individuals were injured.

Ten Libyan youths protested in the lobby of a Tripoli hotel where Egyptian ruler Hussein Tantawin was speaking. The demonstraters demanded the return of former Khadafi loyalists in Egypt and expressed support for fellow revolutionaries in Egypt.
Over one hundred armed Khadafi loyalists known as Brigade 93 attacked Bani Walid. Four were killed and many more injured.

As members of the Syrian National Council took control of the Syrian embassy in Tripoli, dozens of suppoters gathered outside to protest the rule of Bashar al-Assad. The following day, roughly two hundred Syrians broke into the Russian embassy and raised the Syrian rebel flag to protest Russia's UN vetoes.
After a small initial conflict, extened violence broke out between the Zwai and Tobu. Heavy weapson were used and over one hunder people were killed, including numerous civilians
In an effort to discourage a pro-Khadafi resurgence, Libya unitied militia forces held a military parade through Tripoli.
Thousands of Libyan gathered in Benghazi's Tahrir Square to celebrate the anniversary of the revolt that overthrew Khadafi.
Members of the Saraya Swehli militia kidnapped two British journalists and their three Libyan companions.
Angry Salafist protesters desecrated WWII graves in Benghazi in response to U.S. troops in Afghanistan burning the Koran.
Thousands protested in Benghazi and Tripoli at the prospect of a federal system of governance. One individual was killed as protesters set fire to a Benghazi market.
Thousands protested in Benghazi and Tripoli at the prospect of a federal system of governance. One individual was killed as protesters set fire to a Benghazi market.

Following a speech by pro-federalist leader Ahmed Zubeir Senussi, two thousand federalist supporters clashed with anti-federalists. One individual was killed in the conflict and five others were injured.
Arab tribesmen clashed with Tabu  in Sabha. The ethnically fueled conflict produced around one hundred and sixty-three deaths and wounded hundreds others.

Around thirty former rebels belonging to the Katibat al-Awfiya militia held a sit-in protest at Benghazi's airport. The demonstrators demanded government compensation for their servince in the revolt.

The militia Ragdalein captured men from Zwara because of alleged looting and abuses during the previous year's revolt. Zwara's forces attacked in response and seventeen individuals were killed and dozens others wounded.

The militia Ragdalein captured men from Zwara because of alleged looting and abuses during the previous year's revolt. Zwara's forces attacked in response and seventeen individuals were killed and dozens others wounded.
Five Tunisians were captured in the Tunisian-Libyan and held hostage for two days.

Former rebels held small demonstrations in front of the interim government building in Tripoli and constructed several blockades throughout the city. The militiamen were angered by the government's decision to suspend compensation to rebels. The government's headquarters were fired upon, but no injuries were reported.
A convoy of UN officials travelling in Benghazi was attacked with a hand grenade. No injuries occurred and the assailant remained unidentified.
Armed Libyans detained Tunisian workers and demanded freedom for a small group of Libyans held in Tunisia.
Elements of the national army attacked members of the Tobu in Kufra. The conflict produced twelve deaths and many more deaths.
Prisoners in Benghazi made a violent attempt at escape, but were stopped by guards. Three guards and three prisoners were killed.
Unknown individuals damaged a courthouse in Benghazi using explosive devices. The attack wounded three individuals.
A demonstration of dozens of former rebels ended peacefully when leader of the National Transitional Council Abdel Jalil came out of the NTC headquarters and placated the crowd.
Police killed two militiamen in Tripoli after the former revolutionaries refused to cede control of territory in the capital.

Militiamen, some from Yefran, surrounded the government headquarters in Tripoli and protested the government's refusal to compensate former rebels as well as its failure provide medical care to the wounded. The protesters then turned violent and one individual was killed and four injured in the subsequent fray.
A group of armed individuals killed Khaled Abu Saleh outside of Ubari. Saleh had just registered in an upcoming General National Congress election.

A group of Tuareg tribesmen attacked the town of Ghadames in response to their expulsion from Ghadames and several other communities. Six Tuaregs and one citizen of Ghadames were killed during the attack.

target1: International Committee of the Red Cross
issuenote: Assailants hit the International Committiee of the Red Cross's office in Benghazi with an RPG. No casualties occurred.
Unknown individuals struck the Benghazi branch of Sahara Bank with a rocket, causing some damage, but no injuries.
Tarhouna militiamen forcefully seized Tripoli's airport in response to their leader's arrest. Government forces retook the airport several hours later.
Assailants struck the U.S. diplomatic mission in Benghazi with a bomb. Minimal damage was incurred and no one was wounded.

Dozens of activists, including women, held a protest in Benghazi to criticize other demonstrators for bringing weapons to a rally in support of Sharia law. The activists successfully dispered the Sharia rally.
Over three hundred heavily armed men protested in Benghazi's Tahrir Square just before Libya's assembly election. The demonstrators demanded Libya be ruled under Sharia law.

Members of the Tobu minority attacked a government checkpoint. The Libya Shield Brigade, an element of the national army, retaliated with an assault on Kufra. Twenty Tobu and three soldiers were killed.
Unknown assailants attacked a British diplomatic convoy in Benghazi with a RPG. Two British bodyguards were injured in the attack.

Zintan rebels attacked members of the el-Manshisha, a rival tribe that did not participate in the anti-Gadhafi uprising. The attack was a response to the shooting of a Zintan rebel by alleged el-Manshisha members. Twelve individuals were killed and eighty-nine wounded in the retaliation.

target1: International Committee of the Red Cross

In response to widespread violence and insecurity, dozens of Libyans protested in Benghazi. The demonstrators requested  the government control the militias and reinstate order.
Assailants fired on a security patrol traveling in Sabha, killing two and wounding ten.
Unidentified individuals destroyed the headstones of WWII Allied soldiers in Benghazi. The graves were believed to be targeted for religious reasons.
Armed members of the Partisans of Shariah seized the Tunisian consulate in Benghazi, but eventually withdrew peacefully.
In Derna, unknown individuals killed former Khadafi officers and other individuals in a series of killings that extended over months.

In Kufra, Tobu tribesmen clashed with members of the Zwai tribe. The Libya Shield Brigade attempted to stop the fighting, but was drawn into the conflict. Around thrity-two individuals, including women and children, were killed and many more wounded.

Abdel-Hakim Belhaj, leader of the Al-Watan party, spoke to hundreds about the need for Sharia in Libya's emerging democracy. The rally in Tripoli occurred a week before national elections.
Supporters of federalism attempted to attack a warehouse containing national election ballots but were peacefully stopped by residents of Ajdabiya. The following day, the ballots were burnt.
The Alliance for National Forces led a parade of cars through Tripoli to advocate their party in the upcoming election.
Members of the Justice and Construction Party held a march through Tripoli in anticipation of upcoming elections.

Unknown individuals fired two rockets at the Benghazi Medical Centre, failing to cause any casualities or damage.
Unidentified gunmen attacked polling stations in several locations throughout Libya. In Ajdabiya, one individual was killed and two injured.
In Benghazi, hundreds of protesters burned ballots and asked the government to provide greater democracy.

Hundreds of Libyans gathered in Tripoli and Benghazi to celebrate the country's first post-Gadhafi election. In Benghazi, military members participated in the demonstration, but once they left protester became violent and destroyed property.

Khadafi loyalists kidnapped Omran Ben Shaaban, the man responsible for Khadafi's capture, and three of his associates. Shaaban was shot while trying to escape. Later released, he died of the injuries received during his captivity.

issuenote: One person was wounded in Tripoli during a fight over market space. The conflict featured gunfire and a car bomb.

target1: International Committee of the Red Cross
issuenote: Unknown individuals attacked the residence of Red Cross workers in Misrata with heavy weaponry.
In Al-Aziziya, a unit of the interior ministry brigade raided the hideout of individuals tied to several bomb plots. Three suspects were killed and five security officers wounded.
Derna's city security chief was killed by unknown individuals.
Khadafi loyalists detonated two bombs in Tripoli, targeting a military academy and an office of the interior ministry. Two individuals were killed and four injured in the attacks.

Security forces attacked Katibat al-Awfiya, a pro-Khadafi militia, near Tarhuna. One individual was killed, eight injured, and thirteen arrested. Additionally, over one hundred tanks and other heavy weaponry were seized.
Two rival tribes in Zliten attacked each other with light and heavy weaponry in an attempt to settle a long-standing dispute. Two individuals were killed.
Islamic fundamentalists destroyed Sufi shrines in Tripoli, Misrata, and Zliten because they viewed the idea of worhipping tombs as sacrilegious.

Dozens of Libyans protested in Tripoli in response to the government's inability to deal with religious violence.
Islamic radicals, long abused under Khadafi, planted and detonated a bomb in the car of colonel of the former regime. The colonel was killed and his assistant wounded.
Muslim fundamentalists attempted  to destroy a shrine in Rajma, but were stopped by local militia and national security forces. Three individuals were killed and many others wounded.

Islamic terrorists laid seige to the United States consulate in Benghazi, killing U.S. Ambassador Christopher Stevens and three other diplomats. Several others were wounded. The attack was conducted by around fifty militants armed with grenades and guns.
Members of Ansar al-Sharia beat and stabbed Catholic nuns and  a priest in Derna.
Hundreds of protesters gathered in Tripoli and Benghazi to condem the terrorist attack against the U.S. consolate in Benghazi days earlier.
Hundreds of protesters gathered in Tripoli and Benghazi to condem the terrorist attack against the U.S. consolate in Benghazi days earlier.
Derna residents held a lengthy sit-in protest outside the Sahaba Mosque and called for the disbanding of Ansar al-Sharia, a militant group responsible for recent violence.
About two hundred individuals belonging to the Ansar al-Shariah militia marched through Benghazi to express their faith in Muhammad and anger over an anti-Muslim film.
Air traffic controllers at Libya's international airports in Tripoli and Benghazi went on strike to demand better salaries and equipment.
Air traffic controllers at Libya's international airports in Tripoli and Benghazi went on strike to demand better salaries and equipment.
Khadafi loyalists entered into an extended conflict with pro-government militia in Barek al-Shati. Ninteen individuals were killed and thirty militiamen were captured.
notes: Article listed number of deaths as almost twenty

target1: Ansar al-Sharia and other Islamist militias
issuenote: march organized by Mohammed Abujanah and others to protest the continued presence of militias. Activists attempted to violently oust Ansar al-Sharia and other Islamist militias from their bases. Eleven individuals, including security forces, were killed and about seventy injured. The city residents were particularly angered by Ansar al-Sharia's religious fanatacism and possible link to Ambassador Chris Steven's death.

In Benghazi, hundreds of members of Ansar al-Sharia protested the creation of anti-Muslim film by an amatuer U.S. film producer and an offensive French cartoon. The protesters also criticized U.S. President Barack Obama while praising God.
The national army forcefully removed militias in Tripoli still lingering from anti-Khadafi uprising.
Over two hundred Salafist protesters demanded the return of extremist militia Ansar al-Sharia to Benghazi. The protesters grew violent and attacked security forces with grenades and burned cars.
Around two hundred protesters marched in Tripoli, asking the government to disband militias and create a more centralized security force.
Khadafi loyalists from Bani Walid clashed with militiamen from Misrata in the valley of Mardun, just outside of the loyalists' town. Three militiamen were wounded.
Muslim extremists attacked four policeman at a checkpoint in Susa. Three of the officers were killed and the last was left in critical condition.
Over one hundred demonstrators from Zawiyah barged into the national assembly to complain that no one from their city had been selected for the PM's cabinet.
Around one thousand demonstrators gathered outside the national assembly building in Tripoli, requesting the government peacefully end the military seige of Bani Walid.
The Libyan Shield and militia from Misrata laid seige to Bani Walid, believed to be one of the last strongholds of Khadafi loyalists. Thirty individuals were killed and over two hundred were wounded.
In Benghazi, demonstrators looted a private television station after it reported unsubstantiated claims that the government had captured key Khadafi figures.
Armed men attacked the barracks of defense ministry forces in Tripoli. No casualties were reported.

Around two hundred demonstrators gathered outside the national assembly building in Tripoli to protest the seige of Bani Walid. Security forces physically restrained and beat protesters. The demonstration was finally dispersed when government forces fired warning shots into the air.
Hundreds of Libyans gathered in Tripoli and Benghazi to celebrate one year since the country's liberation from the Khadafi regime.
Hundreds of Libyans gathered in Tripoli and Benghazi to celebrate one year since the country's liberation from the Khadafi regime.

About one hundred protesters entered the legislature's building in Tripoli during a vote on the prime minister's cabinet. Protests flared up again in following days as a larger crowd of some two hundred armed demonstrators held a sit-in.
Unknown assailants killed a former Khadafi official in Derna.
Unidentified gunmen killed Muslim cleric Sheikh Abdullah al-Fussay outside a Benghazi mosque.
Over one thousand demonstrators in Benghazi called on the government to adopt a federal system of governance.
Around one hundred and fifty former rebels held a sit-in protest at an oil installation in Zawiya. The men demanded medical care for injuries they sustained during the uprising.
Five were wounded as members of rival militias in Tripoli fought for several hours.
Two unidentified individuals detonated a bomb outside a police station in Benghazi, destroying a car and slightly wounding four officers.
An unknown individual struck a police vehicle with an explosive device. In the ensuing gun battle, one officer was critically wounded and another slightly injured.
Unknown individuals killed former colonel Abdelkarim Mahfud in Benghazi. The colonel was known for supporting the 2011 rebellion.
Unidentified individuals planted bomb in the car of former Khadafi officer Hussam al-Raaid. The explosive device wounded the officer upon detonation.
Three unidentified gunmen fired on Benghazi security chief Fraj al-Dersi, fatally wounding him.
Unknown inidividuals detonated a bomb outside the Al-Fwihet police station in Benghazi. Four officers were were wounded by the blast.
Unidentified gunmen fired on a UN convoy traveling in Khoms. There were no casualties.
Radical Islamists attacked several police stations in Benghazi with guns and RPGs in what appeared to be an attempt to free a murder suspect. Four policemen were killed and three wounded.
During the attempted arrest of murder suspect in Bani Walid, two soldiers were gunned down by unidentified attackers.
Militiamen in Tripoli protested a military tribunal investigating the death of a military chief by establishing several road blocks.
Over one hundred demonstrators gathered at an oil terminal in Zueitina. The demonstrators demanded jobs and healthcare.
Around two thousand people protested in Benghazi and demanded the government disband all militias.
Two unidentified individuals struck a Coptic church in Dafniya with an explosive device, killing two Egyptians and wounding two others.

A demonstration demanding the release of arrested suspects became violent when Islamists opened fire on the Benghazi police headquarters. Four individuals, including a police officer, were killed and nine others were wounded.
Unknown individuals detonated a bomb outside the public prosecutor's office in Benghazi. The explosion caused damage, but no casualties.
The acting head of the criminal investigations department in Benghazi was kidnapped at gunpoint by bearded men who stopped him at a traffic light
A small number of demonstrators, most of them police officers, gathered to call for the release of kidnapped Lt. Col. Abdel-Salam al-Mahdawi

issuenote: Ugandan LRA rebels attack a displaced persons camp.
geo_comments: about 16 miles north of the Ugandan border

issuenote: 1500 protest US sanctions.
70 women demonstrate in front of the UN offices and deliver a statement calling for the UN to intervene to stop forced recruitment of high school students into the army.
Riots between factions of students over an election to the student union.
Teachers strike over pay issues.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Street traders riot and clash with police.  The police use teargas.
The government stages a rally in which to condemn the United States and warn it against military action in Iraq.
Doctors at El Obeid general hospital strike for higher pay.
notes: Start date is estimated.

issuenote: Bloody clashes erupt when Arabs attack three villages of the non-Arab Mesleit tribe.
Over a 1000 student conscripts try to escape from a military camp.  Soldiers shoot them and beat them, resulting in 74 deaths.  Another 55 drown in the Blue Nile during the escape.
Mothers stand in front of buildings where final exams are administered to prevent security forces from conscripting the students.
notes: Date is estimated.  Reported retrospectively.

issuenote: A riot breaks out at a military training camp, where student conscripts protest against their conscription.  About 70 students escape.
Students protest an increase in university fees and the death of a student in police custody.  The protest devolves into a riot.  Police use tear gas.

Thousands of protesters riot and invade the empty US embassy in retaliation for US air strikes on the Al-Shifa pharmaceutical plant.  About two dozen people protest outside the bombed-out plant.  Large protests continue for the two days.
Thousands protest on the one month anniversary of the US airstrikes.
Factions clash in Kordofan province.
An opposition political party stages protests against restrictions on political parties.
Over a month long period, Arab and African tribes battle over access to dwindling grazing land.
notes: Dates are estimated.  Geneina is in Northern Darfur.

issuenote: Unknown gunmen open fire on the closed US embassy.
Thousands of supporters of the former president Gaafar Nimeiri take to the streets.
Government workers in Northern State strike to demand a promised pay raise.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Angry employees who were sacked break in the offices of  the SCB and express their views to the management.  The protesters say the management took no notice of the economic conditions of employee families.
Thousands of demonstrators, mainly school children, march to protest an attack on an oil pipeline by the National Democratic Alliance and the Umma Party, rebel opposition groups.
After the government denies a female student's admission to university because of her allegedly indecent dress, 500 students pour out of two universities and march into the Khartoum city center.
After the government denies a female student's admission to university because of her allegedly indecent dress, 500 students pour out of two universities and march into the Khartoum city center.
The government organizes a pro-government protest to condemn the rebel Umma Party and its bombing of an oil pipeline.
Government workers in West Bahr al-Ghazal State strike to protest pay cuts by the state government.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Government police raid an office of the opposition DFF, beating journalists and lawyers for contacting John Garang, leader of the SPLA.
Three Russian nationals stage a hunger strike to protest breach of contract by a Sudanese aviation firm.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: A protest organized by the DUP in opposition to the Islamist backed military government.  The protest escalated with the demonstrators throw Molotov cocktails.  The police repress with tear gas.
More than 500 south Sudanese students demonstrate outside the US embassy to deliver a petition to the US special envoy demanding self-determination for the south.
200 Ethiopians stage a hunger strike against a UN decision to strip them of their refugee status.
Tens of thousands protest against rebel victories in east Sudan.
Workers at one of Sudan's largest banks stage a strike to demand a doubling of salaries.
Students protest against the listing of Sudan as a terrorist sponsoring state by the US.
Police attack students of Sennar University who arrived to listen to lectures by Democratic Forces Front leaders.  Riots then ensue.  The clashes leave one dead after police fire into the crowd.
Thousands of students protest over clashes in Sennar between fellow students and the police.  The police use tear gas.
Civilians riot after a military truck strikes a civilian on a bicycle who they believed was being chased in order to forcibly conscript him.
notes: Reported retrospectively.

issuenote: A late payment of teacher's salaries delays the start of classes, causing students to riot.  One death.  The students also protest lack of access to electricity and water.

Students protest against school fees and a shortage of textbooks and denounce the regional government of Red Sea State.  Police use tear gas after the protesters begin pulling down telephone poles and blocking roads.
Students riot against mandatory military service.  The unemployed join them.  The police respond with force and kill two.
Protesters demonstrate against the arrest of opposition leaders.  Police use tear gas in Nyala.
Doctors on their national service strike because their allowances haven't been paid.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Protesters demonstrate against the arrest of opposition leaders.  Police use tear gas in Nyala.
University students stage anti-government protests.  The police respond with tear gas.
Students protest the imposition of new school fees and shortages of teachers.  Police use tear gas.
University students chanting anti-government slogans open fire on riot police.  The group is organized by the Popular National Congress, headed by Hassan al-Turabi, the former speaker of Parliament.
A gunman from the extremist Takfir wal-Hijra opens fire on worshippers at a mosque belonging to the pacifist Ansar al-Sunna.
30 people protest outside the General Election Commission due to a delay in vote counting.  They are put down by police with tear gas.
Christians protest against a decision by authorities to move an Easter ceremony.
Hijackers take control of an airplane over Ethiopia to bring attention to the economic and political situation there.  They land in Khartoum and release the hostages.
University students riot over the measures affecting the examination system.  Police use force, one student is killed.
A Popular Nation Congress official is killed by the police when they try to arrest him, triggering protests the next day.  The police use tear gas against them.
Students riot to demand the sacking of a faculty member.
Students denounce US strikes on Afghanistan and support Osama bin Laden.

actor1: Sudanese Popular Organization for Solidarity with the Afghan People
issuenote: 8000 protesters march to condemn US strikes on Afghanistan.
Prison inmates begin a hunger strike which escalates into a riot.  The police use clubs and tear gas.  The prisoners gain access to firearms and kill 2 guards.  5 inmates killed.
More than 1000 demonstrators led by Arab parliamentarians protest against Israel and pledge support for the Palestinians.

actor1: A grouping of unions, professional organizations, and student groups
issuenote: More than 7000 protesters take to the streets to condemn Israel.
Lord's Resistance Army rebels attack Sudanese army units.
20,000 people march to condemn Israel in response to the Israeli occupation of Ramallah in the West Bank.
notes: Organized by registered political parties, including the ruling National Congress.

issuenote: Thousands of people demonstrate in solidarity with the Palestinians and to condemn the US.
1.5 million people demonstrate against the United States and Israel in response to Israel's occupation of Ramallah in the West Bank.
LRA rebels attack a funeral, forcing mourners to eat the dead body before killing them.

elocal: Idiefe, Obeyok, Kubaya, Lotele, Lohui and Isuhak, three villages in the Magwi county
issuenote: The Ugandan rebel movement, the LRA, flees from  a raid by the Uganda People's Defence Forces on their bases in the southern Sudan town of Katire.  The fleeing rebels attack and burn six villages, killing 470 and committing many atrocities.
notes: The villages are located in the Eastern Equatoria region.  Dates are estimated.

issuenote: The Razaykat tribe attacks the Maaliya to avenge the death of one of their own, a policeman killed by a Maaliya policeman.  The conflict is exasperated by competition over economics and grazing rights.
Members of the al-Nowair tribe clash over an argument in a tribal court, which escalates into riots with tribesmen using knives and swords.  Nine are killed.
A riot erupts between police recruits and residents after a quarrel between a recruit and a resident the week before.  Recruits and civilians armed with guns fire one  another, killing two.
Members of the Islamist Popular National Congress assault the residence of  a senior member of the ruling National Congress.

10 youths belonging to an Islamic organization throw rocks and gas canisters at the house of the energy and mining minister.  They chant Islamist slogans and support the opposition Popular National Congress.
Students stage an anti-government riot because of the authorities refusal to allow students to commemorate the October revolution of 1964 which brought down Sudan's first military regime.
Students stage sit ins to demand the government investigate police brutality during the riots of 10/22/2002.
Pro and anti government students riot, throw Molotov cocktails at each other.
Pro and anti government students riot, throw Molotov cocktails at each other.
Tribes riot following the stabbing death of a tribal leader.  6 die in total.
Over 10,000 people protest against the impending US attack on Iraq.
Tribesmen clash with the government.
notes: This event is coded because it occurs before the onset of civil war in Darfur in the Uppsala database.

issuenote: Protesters demonstrate against the Iraq War.  Riot police shoot dead a university student.

notes: UPPSALA CONFLICT #113

issuenote: Tribes clash in South Darfur.
notes: Date is estimated.  Event is reported retrospectively.  Presumably, this event has to do with grazing rights, but the article makes no mention of this.

actor1: Student supporters of the African National Front
actor2: Supporters of the National Democratic Alliance
issuenote: Student loyal to opposition parties stage a violent protest for student union elections.  They assault and hold hostage several lecturers and students.  They battle with riot police.
20 students riot to demand that their diplomas be upgraded to degrees.
Students riot over deteriorating conditions in their boarding houses and battle with riot police.
Teachers strike over pay delays.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: High school students protest a teacher strike by attacking and setting fire to offices of the Blue Nile state's education ministry.
A peaceful demonstration by university students calling on the UN and the international community to intervene in Darfur.  Riot police suppress with tear gas and batons.

actor1: Izzat Salam Al-Sudan (Dignity of Peace in Sudan)
issuenote: An NGO organizes a march of hundreds of children, calling on the government and the rebels to end the civil war.
Three people are killed in a riot at a Sudanese refugee camp.
notes: Could not determine a cause, other than some government propaganda about saboteurs.

issuenote: Thousands of Sudanese protest Israel's assassination of Hamas leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin.
About 300 disabled Sudanese protest against Israel's assassination of Hamas leader Sheik Ahmed Yassin.
Students gather to protest against the detention of several of their comrades.  The even escalates and the students torch a building.  The police react by firing indiscriminately into the crowd.

actor1: Popular Congress officials, members, and sympathizers
issuenote: 71 imprisoned Islamists stage a hunger strike against their detainment.  They are eventually released on the 17th, although Hassan al-Turabi, an opposition leader, remains on strike until the 25th when he is hospitalized.
LRA rebels wage a campaign of violence against Sudanese villages and are attacked by Ugandan Army.
32 jailed Sudanese Islamists stage a hunger strike against their detention without trail or charge.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: Tens of thousands of Sudanese march against foreign intervention in the Darfur crisis.  They denounce a plan by the African Union to deploy peacekeepers, as well as the US.
Government security forces enter a refugee camp and force the refugees to move to another camp.  Government forces use tear gas.
LRA rebels attack a Sudanese village.
Beja tribesmen begin protesting against economic conditions but then begin looting and burning shops.  The government forces fire into the crowd, killing 14.
notes: Competing death claims.  The govt claims 14, the Beja Congress claims 36.

issuenote: Students at Gezira university riot over disputed student elections.  The university's facilities are spread out among many towns in Gezira State.  Students burn and pillage buildings in Hilaliah and Hassaheisah.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: Students at Gezira university riot over disputed student elections.  The university's facilities are spread out among many towns in Gezira State.  Students burn and pillage buildings in Hilaliah and Hassaheisah.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: LRA rebels ambush several Sudanese citizens.

elocal: Road between Ed-Daen and Nyala in South Darfur
ilocal: Road between Ed-Daen and Nyala in South Darfur
issuenote: Gun attack and kill contractors.
Police arrive at a refugee camp to forcibly move the refugees.  They form a huge crowd and drive off the police and then burn a nearby police station.  3 police and 14 rioters are killed.
Thousands of Muslims gather outside the American embassy to protest alleged desecrations of the Koran at Guantanamo Bay.
Students angered by the make up of a committee appointed to organize union polls burns down nine buildings in Omdurman.
Armed men attack aid workers at refugee camps in El Geneina.
Men armed with sticks and rocks raid a refugee camp.  Two villagers die.
41 detainees from the Popular Congress, including Hassan al-Turabi, and from Darfur stage a hunger strike against their detention.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: LRA rebels attack a refugee camp.
John Garang, leader of the Sudan People's Liberation Army, dies in a helicopter crash.  Arabs and Africans riot in Khartoum and Juba.
notes: Malalka also known as Malakal.

issuenote: John Garang, leader of the Sudan People's Liberation Army, dies in a helicopter crash.  Arabs and Africans riot in Khartoum and Juba.
notes: Malalka also known as Malakal.

issuenote: John Garang, leader of the Sudan People's Liberation Army, dies in a helicopter crash.  Arabs and Africans riot in Khartoum and Juba.
notes: Malalka also known as Malakal.

issuenote: LRA rebels attack several Sudanese villages.
Unknown gunmen kill 2 AU peacekeepers.
Ugandan rebels attack and kill two UN demining contractors.
Rebels kill a British aid worker.
notes: Date is estimated.

issuenote: Two tribes clash, resulting in an unknown number of deaths, including at least one aid worker for Catholic Relief Services.

About 50,000 people protest against the publication of Danish cartoons caricaturing the Prophet Mohammed, demanding that Danish and European diplomats be expelled and urging Al-Qaeda to attack Denmark.
Protesters throw stones at the offices of a Danish NGO over the publication of cartoons caricaturing the Prophet Mohammed.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: Protesters throw stones at the offices of a Danish NGO over the publication of cartoons caricaturing the Prophet Mohammed.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: Scores of students and women demonstrate near the US embassy to protest a campaign by the US to deploy an international force in Darfur.

actor1: Popular Organization for the Defense of the Homeland and the Faith
issuenote: Tens of thousands protest against plans by the AU and the UN to deploy peacekeepers into Darfur.

The government plans to build a dam on the Nile River, and citizens riot over the lack of compensation and resettlement options.  Up to 1000 protesters attack police guarding census workers who are in the area.
notes: Coded for environmental degradation.

issuenote: About 1000 refugee protesters riot at the Kalma camp to demand that UN peacekeepers be deployed to the region in order to protect them.  They attack and kill a translator, accusing him of working with the Janjaweed.
Refugees in camps riot to protest a peace deal signed between the government and the rebels.  Protesters and police exchange gun fire.  Six are killed.
Refugees in camps riot to protest a peace deal signed between the government and the rebels.  Protesters and police exchange gun fire.  Six are killed.
Up to 5000 demonstrators protest against UN and US plans to deploy peacekeepers in Darfur.
Thousands of students condemn Israeli attacks in Lebanon and Gaza and voice their support for Hezbollah.
Several dozen Sudanese protest a visit by the top US State Department official for Africa.
Several thousand protesters demonstrate against sugar and fuel price hikes.
A group claiming to be al-Qaeda's branch in Sudan claims responsibility for the murder of journalist Mohammed Taha Mohammed Ahmed, who was kidnapped and killed over charges of blasphemy.
notes: Reported retrospectively.

issuenote: Around 100 journalists stage a strike for a week to protest against a recent wave of censorship.
notes: End date is estimated.

issuenote: About 150 people protest against the UN over a proposed plan to deploy peacekeepers to Darfur.  This is a counter-protest to a wave of rallies around the world that call for an end to the Darfur violence.
About 6000 people march to protest against Pope Benedict XVI over comments he made about Islam.  Protest appears organized by youth organizations.
Unknown gunmen, believed by many to be the Ugandan Lord's Resistance Army, attack and kill 38 civilians in a string of attacks.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: A former rebel and five police officers die in a shootout in Khartoum.  The government describes the incident as isolated, but a southern official said it was a foiled assassination attempt.
notes: Reported retrospectively.  Date is estimated.

issuenote: A string of incidents involving attacks on farmers around the Kalma refugee camp by Arab nomads.
notes: This event appears independent of the civil war dynamic.

issuenote: A battle erupts between the SPLA and SSDF.  SSDF is a pro-government militia, while SPLA is the main rebel group in South Sudan.
notes: Coded as anti-government violence as the SPLA now governs south Sudan.

issuenote: After a battle in which the National Redemption Front rebels attack and destroy a civilian convoy, killing 30 refugees and aid workers near Sirba, civilians riot outside the UN compound.
Refugees related to 30 civilians killed by the National Redemption Front riot at the AU base to protest the peacekeeper's failure to protect them.  The peacekeepers fire into the crowd, killing 3.
Two AU peacekeepers and a Nigerian mayor are abducted and their car stolen by gunmen in the capital of North Darfur.

700 fighters of the Sudan People's Liberation Army protest against the non-payment of their salaries.  They shoot their weapons skywards, spreading panic.  A pedestrian is killed by a speeding motorist seeking to avoid the gunfire.
One policeman is killed when unknown gunmen attack a patrol
Police pursue a man who attacked someone with a knife into an Anglican mass.  The police use tear gas and batons on the Anglicans as they try to flee the church.
A tribal clash erupts in the locality of BulBul Abu Angra.
LRA rebels ambush citizens.

actor1: Popular Organization for the Defense of the Faith
issuenote: A protest organized against the execution of Saddam Hussein.  The government represses with tear gas, batons, and whips.

Sudan's two main television stations (Blue Nile TV and Omdurman Radio) go off the air for three minutes to protest against the detention of a Sudanese cameraman in Guantanamo Bay.  More than 2000 staff stop working during the blackout.
Clashes between rival student groups at Al-Nilayn University sets off over a week of further clashes.  One group supports the ruling National Congress Party, the other supports the SPLM of the south.
150 interpreters working for the AU peacekeeping force strike over unpaid wages and higher salaries.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: Two tribes clash over livestock raiding and grazing rights.  Torjam nomads descend on a Rzigat village.  62 die.
Gunmen kill 5 Senegalese AU peacekeepers.  Senegal blames the SLA rebels.

elocal: Abu Gorah sector of North Darfur
ilocal: Abu Gorah sector of North Darfur
issuenote: Two tribes clash, resulting in 62 deaths.  11 villages are looted.  Clash erupts over livestock raiding and grazing rights.
Toposa cattle raiders attack the village of Lauro Payam, killing 54 people.
More than 100 people stage a sit-in outside the offices of an independent daily newspaper that was shut down after criticizing the justice minister.
Several hundred protest outside the US embassy against the imposition of new sanctions over the war in Darfur.
Protesters demonstrate against a dam project they say will destroy their community.  Police use live rounds on the demonstrators after they attack construction equipment.
Dozens of journalists protest against the detention of four colleagues who reported on the demonstration in Farraig in which 4 people were killed (6/14/2007).
Bandits attack a food program convoy and ransom the drivers.
Two Arab tribes clash over grazing rights and livestock raiding.
notes: The article specifically mentions that the date is unknown.  As such, the date reported here is estimated.

issuenote: Two Arab tribes clash over grazing rights and livestock raiding.
Two southern Sudan tribes clash over cattle during a two week period, leaving 34 dead.
notes: Dates are estimated.

issuenote: Gunmen attack a MSF compound, killing 4.

A British teacher in Khartoum allows her school children to name a teddy bear Mohammed.  She is arrested and tried by the government, and sentenced to a term in prison.  Protesters gather in Khartoum calling for her death.
Clashes between Misseriya Arab nomads and ex-rebels now governing south Sudan.  Up to 100 killed.  Tensions in the area are attributed to disputed oil wealth.
notes: Classified as anti-government violence, as the SPLA now governs the south.  Coded for ethnic issues and economic assets.  Event reported retrospectively.  Date is estimated.

issuenote: In an act of terrorism, five Islamist gunmen acquire weapons from Atbar and then drive to Khartoum looking for victims.  They end up shooting to dead an American aid worker and his Sudanese driver.
Previously unknown extremist group kills a US diplomat.
Gunmen of the Salamat Arab tribe storm a prison, freeing 90 detainees.
Several thousand students demonstrate against the Israeli blockade of the Gaza Strip.
LRA rebels attack Sudanese villages.
Tens of thousands of people protest against Danish cartoons satirizing the Prophet Muhammad.
A clash erupts between the nomadic Arab Misseriya tribe and ex-rebels now governing south Sudan.  78 killed.  Tensions in the area stem from disputes over oil wealth.
A spate of attacks by gunmen on WFP drivers.  One occurs on the road to Nyala, the other in south Sudan.  3 WFP drivers killed.
Protests occur at a refugee camp.  Refugees accuse the Arab dominated government of manipulating a forthcoming census.
notes: There are 3 deaths due to shooting at the camp, but these appear to be criminal related.

issuenote: Fighting erupts when Arab tribes attack a garrison of South Sudan forces whom they claim should not be in the disputed region according to a peace agreement.
Tribesmen abduct four Indian oil workers.
notes: Reported retrospectively.  Date is estimated.

issuenote: The former rebels of South Sudan attack Abyei, under control of the northern government in a dispute over oil claims.
notes: Event occurs in the town of Abyei, not to be confused with the region of the same name.  Coded for intra-government violence.  Sudan Defense Force is the army of the north, while the south is a semi-autonomous, self-governing region at this poi

issuenote: Thousands of people demonstrate at a government organized 'victory' rally to denounce Darfur rebels who staged a daring attack on the capital.  They condemn the rebels as agents of Israel.
LRA rebels attack multiple villages, looting and killing several.
LRA rebels attack multiple villages, looting and killing several.
200 gunmen attack a UN patrol, killing 7.  The janjaweed is strongly suspected.

The ICC indicts president Omar el-Bashir on war crimes charges.  A couple hundred Bashir supporters rally outside his palace.  Later in the day, a hundred or so lawyers protest outside the French embassy.
notes: Protest is organized by ruling party.

issuenote: 1500 students and Arab tribesmen protest to show support for president Omar el-Bashir and to condemn an indictment against him from the International Criminal Court.
notes: Organized by ruling party.

issuenote: 1500 students and Arab tribesmen protest to show support for president Omar el-Bashir and to condemn an indictment against him from the International Criminal Court.
notes: Organized by ruling party.

issuenote: Thousands of people organized by the government protest against an ICC indictment and rally to support the president.
Thousands of people organized by the government protest against an ICC indictment and rally to support the president.
Thousands of people organized by the government protest against an ICC indictment and rally to support the president.
Hundreds of refugees in a refugee camp stage demonstrations against the government after an army raid that left 25 dead.
notes: Date is estimated.  The army raid itself is a part of the civil war dynamic, and thus is not coded.

issuenote: Hausa gather to protest a new report quoting the president as saying the Hausa are not Sudanese.  They clash with police.  One Hausa and one police officer die.
Unknown armed men ambush UN peacekeepers, killing 1.
Two newspaper stop work for three days and their workers go on a hunger strike for 24 hours to protest against government censorship.
Journalists protest against censorship and the arrest of dozens of their colleagues.
A clash between the Arab Habaniya and the African Falatta tribes.  The clash erupts over cattle thefts and other ethnic issues.  15 civilians die.  3 police die when they try to break up the fight.

A scuffle erupts between police and an Arab butcher who refuses to move to a new town market.  The argument escalates to a riot in the town.  The police fire on the crowd.  Soldiers, believing they're under attack, return fire on the police.
notes: Details are scarce, but presumably the clash between soldiers and police has to do with the divide between north and south in Abyei.

issuenote: A local anti-SPLA militia leader, Gabriel Tangginyang, clashes with SPLA/South Sudan forces.  At least 75 die.
Tens of thousands protest in support of the president as the ICC prepares to issue a warrant against him.
Ethnic groups clash over cattle.
notes: Reported retrospectively.  Dates are estimated.  Coded for ethnic issues, economic assets, and food insecurity due to ongoing famine.

issuenote: Thousands of people, including government employees, stage a protest against an ICC arrest warrant issued against president Omar al-Bashir.  The crowd condemns the ICC and shows support for the president.  Some of the protesters condemn the US.
Gunmen ambush and wound four UN peacekeepers.
Gunmen abduct 3 MSF workers.
A few dozen protesters demonstrate against the execution of rebels from Darfur.  Police break up with tear gas.
Ethnic groups clash over cattle.  Murles attack Lou Nuer villages, killing and abducting many.
notes: Dates are estimated.  Coded for ethnic issues, economic assets, and food insecurity due to ongoing famine.

issuenote: Jailed Islamists stage a hunger strike.
Continued warfare between ethnic groups over rights to cattle grazing.  Murle gunmen attack a group of displaced Lou Nuer, killing 185, including many women and children.
Just over 100 women protest the arrest, trial, and flogging of women on indecency charges (specifically, the women are charged with wearing trousers).  The police break up the protest with tear gas.

Lou Nuer raiders attack a small Dinka Bor settlement in the Twic East region of Jonglei state in order to steal cattle.  SPLA troops respond.  A battle erupts and 46 die.  Around 70 troops battle with an equal number of raiders.
Shilluk tribal militia attack Dinka villages, killing around 20.  Dinka retaliate on the Shilluk village of Bon, killing around 5.
Shilluk tribal militia attack Dinka villages, killing around 20.  Dinka retaliate on the Shilluk village of Bon, killing around 5.

Lou Nuer raiders attack a Dinka village over cattle grazing rights.  A battle erupts.  80 people die.  The Lou Nuer militia deliberately South Sudan security forces as well.
Tribes clash over ethnic issues, cattle grazing, and access to natural resources.
Tribes clash over ethnic issues, cattle grazing, and access to natural resources.
Gunmen abduct a French Red Cross worker.

The SPLA organizes a protest against the the president, calling on him to amend laws to ensure free elections.  The police use tear gas and batons to break up the demonstration, triggering riots elsewhere.

SPLA/Ummah/opposition organized protest to demand the president and the ruling party amend laws to ensure free and fair elections in April 2010.  Police respond with tear gas and arrests.
Clashes occur between SPLA forces and civilian cattle keepers.
Rival tribal groups clash, resulting in 140 deaths and 30,000 stolen head of cattle.

ilocal: New Fangak region of Jonglei state
issuenote: Ethnic groups clash.
Ethnic Dinka SPLA forces clash with Messeriya Arabs over cattle.
Rek Dinka attack a Gok Dinka weapons depot, resulting in a battle.  SPLA forces intervene to stop the fighting.
Rival clans of the Dinka ethnic group clash over cattle.
Fighting breaks out between Arabs and SPLA forces as tensions rise over elections, ethnic issues, and the distribution of oil revenue.
A clash occurs between SPLA and ruling party supporters during a presidential election.
notes: Issue type is disputed.  NCP claims SPLA killed several of their supporters in election related violence.  SPLA claims it was a dispute over adultery.

issuenote: Supporters of a defeated candidate for governorship of Unity state protest.  Police shoot dead 2 protesters.

Muslim extremists bomb two police patrols and two shops and stab a Coptic Christian pharmacist in apparent retaliation for the fatal shooting of an extremist in a police raid on 8-Nov-92.

Police detain over 200 Muslim extremists (all allegedly members of al-Gama'a al-Islamiyya) after learning they were plotting to seize police stations and banks in Assiut (and in response to recent violence in that area).

issuenote: Students at girls' secondary school argue over tape played by one (Muslim) girl deemed by another (Christian) girl to be offensive to Christianity.

Students and citizens hold numerous demonstrations throughout Cairo in protest of the Hebron massacre and the Egyptian government's unsatisfactory response.
Members of the Lawyers' Syndicate engage in strikes and later hold an organized demonstration in protest of the death of a colleague who died in police custody.

3000 workers at a state textile factory go on strike to protest the non-payment of bonuses and allowances for months and to support 2,000 colleagues who had been laid off or moved to administrative positions.

Twenty writers and intellectuals demonstrate in protest of the (non-lethal) stabbing of Nobel Prize-winning author Naguib Mahfouz by Islamic radicals and the government's failure to stand up for intellectual freedom.

Members of 21 professional unions stand silently in front of parliament to protest a bill that would give the Egyptian government a bigger hand in union politics; several days later.  They later strike.
notes: There are conflicting estimates of the number of participants--one article estimates hundreds of thousands, while another estimates tens of thousands;    Also, the end date is unclear.

issuenote: Inhabitants of two villages (Abu Daud and San Saft) in northern Egypt fight with knives, axes, and gas-bottles over a shared football (soccer) pitch, injuring 50 and destroying 20 homes and stables.

notes: Unsure if a news conference counts as a demonstration, but since it was blocked by police, it seems as if the government certainly considered it as such; unsure if simply blocking the way counts as repression.

issuenote: Dozens of villagers opposed to Egypt's ruling National Democratic Party pelted a government candidate in the upcoming parliamentary elections with stones during a campaign stop, injuring him slightly.
Palestinians expelled from Libya by Col. Gadhafi lay in the main road between Libya and Egypt for 16 hours, closing the border to traffic and brawling with Egyptians trying to cross.
notes: End date is an estimate.

issuenote: Dozens of students demonstrate on the campus of Cairo University, calling for the release of Muslim Brotherhood members imprisoned in the recent government crackdown.

issuenote: Villagers in Abu Shendi in the northern Nile Delta region riot when police confront them with a court order ordering them to vacate their houses that had been illegally built on another villager's land; police respond with tear gas; one killed.
notes: Unable to find any reliable population info for this village, but it is likely under 100,000.  Also, Npart is an estimate.

issuenote: Police arrest 11 leaders of the opposition Wasat party.
An armed gang robs a bank.

All 12 members of the executive board of Egypt's journalists' union resign in protest of the government's failure to adequately address journalists' appeals to change a controversial law they see as restricting freedom of the press.
About 300 Egyptian lawyers and journalists set fire to an Israeli flag in front of their trade union's headquarters and shout slogans against visiting Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.

elocal: Sinai peninsula, near St. Catherine's Monastery

issuenote: Limited demonstrations, especially student protests, take place in Egypt against Israel and the Egyptian government's policy toward Israel and the Middle East peace process; police arrest over 20 Muslim Brotherhood members.
notes: Info on location, number of participants, etc. is a best estimate.

issuenote: Protesters scuffle with police during a demonstration in opposition to Israel's participation in the Middle East Economic Conference in Cairo; no arrests or injuries reported.
Nearly 1,500 workers at a flour mill go on strike to protest the decision by management to stop selling flour to the workers at subsidized prices.

Over 5,000 Egyptian students and Egyptian women engage in several days of protesting in opposition to Israeli settlement expansion into East Jerusalem; police armed with tear gas and armored vehicles prevent protesters from reaching Israel.

Farmers in several rural areas across Egypt riot, set fire to agricultural ministry buildings, and clash with police in protest against a new agrarian reform law; 24 killed, 349 injured, over 800 arrested.
notes: Start date may be as early as January, but can find no direct info on any violent events prior to June; also, there are differing reports on the number of people killed--24 is the highest number reported.

issuenote: Saudi-owned, London-based daily newspaper Asharq Al-Awsat (The Middle East) closes its Cairo office in protest to what it considers unfair treatment against it in a libel case involving President Hosni Mubarak's two sons.
notes: Unclear how long the newspaper's Cairo office remained closed.

issuenote: Hundreds of potters and artisans in the poor Cairo neighborhood of el-Khawaseen block a street with burning tires and hurl stones at police who had a court order to tear down the artisans' illegally built shops; 73 potters arrested by police.

Three thousand Egyptian Muslims demonstrate at al-Azhar mosque after Friday prayers in protest against Clinton's Iraq policy; days later, over 100 Egyptians, most Muslims, protest outside the U.S. Embassy in Cairo.

Twenty people injured and a dozen cars and several homes damaged as hooligans go on a rampage after the Al-Masri soccer club wins its first Egypt cup in 78 years; police disperse the crowd and arrest several people.

Villagers in Ezbat Wabour el-Nour (about 200 km north of Cairo) riot during the funeral of a man who died after two days in police custody, leaving one dead and 8 injured.  Police respond with tear gas and arrest 25 after villagers throw stones

issuenote: Four hundred taxi drivers and employees working for an Egyptian limousine service go on strike demanding higher wages and social benefits from the Nasser Social Bank.

Thousands of Egyptian citizens, including professionals, university students and schoolchildren, demonstrate in several cities across Egypt in protest against the the British.
Central Bank employees go on strike.
notes: Very little information on the strike was available, as it was only briefly mentioned in connection with another story.

issuenote: Six thousand lawyers protest in the street outside their syndicate after anti-riot police, some armed with batons and rifles, prevented the lawyers from entering at the behest of the government.
Four thousand students at Cairo University protest against Serbian attacks on Kosovo Muslims and call on Arabs and Muslims worldwide to unite to bring the crisis to an end.
Muslim extremists open fire on police in a village in the Assiut region of Upper Egypt, leaving two dead (one policeman and one of the extremists) and two policemen injured.
Three unidentified gunmen shoot and kill a Coptic priest at his monastery's farm.
Armed assailant shot dead by presidential bodyguards after attacking and wounding the Egyptian president with a knife while he was on a tour of northern Egypt.

Soccer fans angered by their team's loss go on a rampage, damaging a car, shop windows, and the nearby local headquarters of President Mubarak's National Party; police respond with tear gas and detain 99 fans.

issuenote: About 3,000 villagers riot, hurling rocks at motorists and setting vehicles ablaze after a speeding truck killed a 16-year-old girl.  Protesters demanded a crackdown on motorists who routinely ignore traffic rules along the route.
About 250 people riot against a police crackdown on contraband goods, overturning a police car but leaving no one hurt.

Villagers clash with police, hurl rocks at a passing train, and set three buses on fire after one of three speeding buses that had been racing each other veered off the road into a group of girls walking to school, killing two of the girls.

The wives of three Islamist journalists jailed for libeling a government minister they said had collaborated with Israel began a sit-in in front of the attorney general's office.  They were joined by several Labor Party leaders.

issuenote: About 8,000 students of Al-Azhar University take to the streets and clash with police, damaging over a dozen police cars and injuring three officers, demanding the resignation of Egypt's culture minister for publishing a novel.

Nearly 200 workers at a Nestle factory in Cairo stage a sit-in protest over a pay dispute with management.

issuenote: Tens of thousands of university students across the country engage in almost daily mass protests against Israeli actions against Palestinians and the Sharm el-Sheikh summit hosted by Egypt.
Fourteen killed, dozens wounded in violence surrounding Egypt's parliamentary elections.  The fighting, which took place near polling stations across the country.

At least 20 journalists covering Egypt's parliamentary elections for both foreign and local media reported being attacked by policemen and plainclothes security men, as well as by some civilians, over the course of four-week election period.
Robbers attack a bank, prompting a gun battle in which local police and civilians are killed.
Around 3,000 students at Cairo University demonstrated peacefully against Israel and Israeli Prime Minister Ariel Sharon under police surveillance without incident.

Leaders of Egypt's journalists' union and leaders of the Cairo-based Arab lawyers' union call a short, symbolic work stoppage to mark what Arabs call Al-Nakba, or the catastrophe of the creation of Israel.

Over 1,000 Coptic Christians protest and riot inside Cairo's Abbasiya cathedral compound, angered by the publication by Al-Nabaa newspaper of pictures of a monk having sex with women inside a monastery in Assiut in southern Egypt.

Egyptians honor a Palestinian-declared labor strike to protest against Israel's seizure of Orient House, a building described in the article as the nerve center for Palestinian nationalist aspirations in Jerusalem.
About 2,000 rioters block the main road from Cairo to Alexandria and riot after a 16-year-old schoolgirl is killed by a motorist.

Muslim and Coptic Christian villagers clash at the inauguration of a new Christian church after an argument over the volume of the church's bells.

Hundreds of thousands of Egyptians hold massive demonstrations and riots on university campuses and mosques across Egypt in outrage at continuing Palestinian-Israeli violence and in opposition to U.S. actions against Iraq.

Hundreds of thousands of citizens hold massive demonstrations across the country in protest against the start of the U.S.-led war in Iraq.  In the last weeks, protests begin to turn violent.
Dozens of members of the leftist Tagammu opposition party rally outside the Egyptian parliament to protest the rising cost of living in Egypt, which they blame on government economic policies.

Around 5,000 students at Menoufia (Menoufia) University demonstrate in protest against U.S. plans for democracy in the Middle East, its support for Israel, and its occupation of Iraq.
Several hundred people gather in Cairo's central Tahrir square to mark the one-year anniversary of the U.S.-led invasion of Iraq and to denounce the U.S. occupation of Iraq.

Tarek al-Zomor, an Egyptian Islamist imprisoned for his involvement in the assassination of former president Sadat stages, a hunger strike over his conditions.

Around 100 demonstrators protest outside Egypt's supreme court in Cairo to urge authorities to halt the use of torture across the country.  The event was organized by several human rights groups and opposition parties.
A confrontation between local police and villagers breaks out as a police officer leads a team in an attempt to evacuate villagers from a sports center built on land owned by that officer.

notes: End date is approximate

issuenote: Multiple bomb blasts hit several hotels packed with European and Egyptian tourists in Egypt's Red Sea resort town of Sharm el-Sheikh, killing at least 88 people and wounding 119.

notes: End date is an estimate

issuenote: A roadside bomb explodes near a military base where international peacekeeping troops charged with protecting the peace treaty between Israel and Egypt, injuring two Canadian peacekeepers.
Police clash with gunmen suspected of connections to the Taba and Sharm el-Sheikh bombings.
Islamists kill two police officers with land mines.

Hundreds of members of the Kefaya movement, a pro-reform coalition, demonstrate in front of the Lawyers' Syndicate in Cairo to encourage Egyptian judges to insist on stronger powers in supervising next week's presidential elections.

About 1,000 protesters march to a state security headquarters in western Cairo where some political detainees have died, chanting slogans and demanding the release of detainees, many of whom are members of the banned Muslim Brotherhood.

Over 500 artists, writers, and intellectuals stage two separate protests against Farouk Hosni, Egypt's culture minister, who offered his resignation in the wake of a September 5 fire in a state-run theater in Beni Suef that killed 42 people.  T

issuenote: After Palestinian and Egyptian border guards seal off the border between Egypt and the Gaza Strip with barbed wire fencing and concrete barriers, Palestinian crowds throw stones at Egyptian and Palestinian border police.

target1: United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)

Thousands of Islamist university students affiliated with the Muslim Brotherhood stage protests on campuses calling for greater freedom on campuses and in national politics.
Tensions between Muslims and Coptic Christians over the DVD release of a Christian play deemed offensive to Islam erupt into violence.
Egyptian police clash with 30 demonstrators, most of them wives, mothers, and children of political detainees, who had gathered outside the Interior Ministry to demand the release of their relatives.
Two journalists covering the parliamentary elections are violently attacked in two separate incidents by unknown assailants who were apparently angered by the journalists' coverage of the elections.

At least 3,000 Muslim Brotherhood supporters stage a demonstration outside the Mustafa Mahmoud mosque in Cairo to protest against the rigged results of the November 9 parliamentary vote; six demonstrators are arrested.
Supporters of the ruling National Democratic Party intimidate and in some cases assault Muslim Brotherhood members and other voters at polling stations around the country.
Several thousand Muslim Brotherhood supporters demonstrate in front of the main counting  center for the Cairo district of Nasr City after polls close on the day of a runoff parliamentary election.

Angry supporters of an independent parliamentary candidate torch the headquarters of the ruling National Democratic Party in the low-income Imbaba district of Cairo after learning that their candidate had lost.

Massive, widespread violence erupts at dozens of polling stations across the country during the second round of parliamentary elections as Muslim Brotherhood supporters, police, and National Democratic Party-hired thugs clash.
notes: Death toll reports vary from 1-3. Npart is an estimate and may be higher.

issuenote: Egyptian security forces clash with suspects of the Sharm el-Sheihk bombings.

Security forces open fire with live ammunition and use tear gas and batons to block opposition voters from casting their ballots at polling stations in opposition strongholds during a second runoff parliamentary election.
notes: Police blamed the Muslim Brotherhood for sparking the violence, but most reports indicate this was not the case and that MB supporters threw stones only in response to violence by police.  I coded these attacks on police by opposition supporter

issuenote: Hundreds of supporters of opposition leader Ayman Nour of the al-Ghad (Tomorrow) party hold multiple demonstrations outside the courtroom where Nour is on trial for forgery charges.
Groups of opposition voters angered at police using tear gas and rubber bullets to block them from voting in the final runoff in Egypt's three-stage parliamentary elections attack police with stones.

Detained opposition leader Ayman Nour of the al-Ghad party, on trial for forgery in what many outside observers view as an attempt by the ruling party to eliminate a political threat, goes on hunger strike to protest his detention.

An altercation between a Muslim and a Christian results in the death of the Muslim.  Muslim villagers later attack the Abu Sifin church and several Christian homes and loot several shops before authorities restore order.

A few hundred supporters of the Kefaya (Enough) movement and its various offshoots demonstrate in central Cairo to protest against the legitimacy of parliamentary elections which it claims were fixed.
Hundreds of angry Palestinians stream across the border from Gaza into Egypt after militants with stolen bulldozers break through a border wall.
Violence erupts between Muslims and Coptic Christians in the town of Al-Udaysat when Muslims torch a Coptic-owned guest house being used as a church without the proper approval from authorities.

Libyan soccer fans at the Cairo International Stadium rip plastic seats from the stands and hurl them at Egyptian riot police during a game between Egypt and Morocco in the Africa Cup of Nations soccer tournament.

target1: National Democratic Party members of Parliament
issuenote: All 88 Muslim Brotherhood members of Egypt's parliament walk out briefly during session to protest the ejection of one of its members.
Tens of thousands of Egyptian citizens hold massive demonstrations and riots in cities across Egypt over the publication of cartoons depicting the prophet Muhammed.
Hundreds of relatives of passengers aboard an Egyptian ferry that sank in the Red Sea gather at the docks in the port city of Safaga.
Hundreds of relatives of passengers aboard an Egyptian ferry that sank in the Red Sea gather at the docks in the port city of Safaga.

A series of street protests by hundreds of people employed in the poultry and related industries take place after a bird flu outbreak prompts the government to order the large-scale culling of birds and to allow more frozen poultry imports.
notes: he start and end dates are estimates

issuenote: Some 50 supporters of a rebel faction within the liberal Wafd opposition party seize control of the party's headquarters and open fire on some 700 Wafd party loyalists.

A psychologically disturbed man fatally stabs an elderly Coptic Christian and wounds at least five other worshippers outside several Coptic churches in Alexandria, sparking three days of rioting and violent clashes between Muslims and Copts.

Three bombs rip through a promenade in Dahab, a resort town located on the Sinai peninsula, killing at least 24 Egyptian and foreign tourists, including a five-year-old German child.
notes: The attacks were claimed by a group calling itself Monotheism and Holy War, which also claimed to be responsible for the two other bombing attacks in the Sinai peninsula.

issuenote: Two suicide bombers target the Multinational Force and Egyptian police.  There are no fatalities.

Government forces clash with suspected terrorists.

Members of the al-Ghad (Tomorrow) party demonstrate outside their party's headquarters following the ruling by an appeals court not to hear the case of former al-Ghad leader Ayman Nour, who was convicted on December 24, 2005, of forgery.
Government forces clash with suspected terrorists.
Some 40 anti-globalization activists protest at the World Economic Forum being held in the resort town of Sharm el-Sheikh.

Pro-reform activists gather outside the Qasr al-Nil police station in Cairo to denounce the alleged torture and sexual abuse of two fellow activists detained there after a May 25 rally; at least three of the protesters are arrested.
Government forces clash with suspected terrorists.

Police use tear gas to disperse hundreds of villagers in the town of Dafash in Minya province who were protesting the fatal stabbing of a fellow Coptic Christian by a Muslim man over a land dispute between the two men.
Some 2,000 Muslim Brotherhood members protest outside a courthouse in Zagazig in support of a senior Brotherhood member on trial there.

Several dozen members of the Journalists' Syndicate demonstrate in front of the syndicate's main offices in Cairo to express their solidarity with three colleagues on trial for denouncing alleged fraud.
Government forces clash with suspected terrorists.

Thousands of demonstrators gather in multiple demonstrations, some organized by the Muslim Brotherhood, in Cairo and the northern province of Damietta to denounce the Israeli offensive in Gaza and to call for a holy war against Israel.

Thousands of demonstrators gather in multiple demonstrations, some organized by the Muslim Brotherhood, in Cairo and the northern province of Damietta to denounce the Israeli offensive in Gaza and to call for a holy war against Israel.

Two dozen members of the Journalists' Syndicate launch a hunger strike at a rally in front in of the syndicate's offices to protest a new law that institutes prison time for journalists who write about the private finances of govt. ministers.

Palestinian militants firing guns force open a border gate between Gaza and Egypt, allowing at least 600 Palestinians stream into Egypt.  Egyptian border police used tear gas and dogs to try to disperse the crowd.

Numerous demonstrations take place in Cairo in protest against the Israeli incursion into Lebanon as thousands of demonstrators call on Arab governments to act to stop the fighting, denounce the United States, and express  support for Hezbollah
